[7] New York (Rockland county): summer camps
Date: Mon 1 Jul 2019 6:25 PM
Source: New York Post [edited]
https://nypost.com/2019/07/01/rockland-county-summer-camps-suing-over-measles-vaccine-requirement/


In a bid to get around local health officials efforts to curb the measles outbreak, a group is suing over the requirement that campers in Rockland county get vaccinated against the highly contagious disease -- and provide the documents to prove it -- arguing that the mandate puts campers' private information at risk.

In the suit, filed [Mon 1 Jul 2019] in federal court in White Plains against Rockland's health commissioner and other officials, the American Camp Association of New York and New Jersey alleges that camps in the county are being held "hostage" by the requirement to turn over an "unprecedented" amount of information about campers with no assurances that the data will be kept safe -- and that the Rockland County Department of Health is using the threat of pulling camps' licenses if it doesn't get its way.

Susie Lupert, the executive director for American Camp Association, said that the 17 summer camps affiliated with her group are already hit with a raft of different regulations that smaller, "single activity" camps -- of which she estimated there are thousands throughout the state -- don't have to face.

Rockland county's new requirement that the camps fork over campers' personal data and health records to government bureaucrats -- which must be done via fax -- puts thousands of campers' privacy at risk, the suit argues.

"I believe that their hearts are in the right place and that they're overreacting," Lupert said of county health officials. Camps that do not show that campers and camp staff have been vaccinated are subject to fines.

Measles outbreaks have affected communities throughout the greater New York area, but Rockland county has been particularly hard hit -- there have been 276 confirmed measles cases since 1 Oct 2018, according to a spokesman for Rockland county.

Earlier this year [2019], the state government eliminated a religious exemption from vaccine requirements, while Rockland county executive Ed Day declared a state of emergency over the outbreak.

In a written statement, Rockland county attorney Thomas Humbach said that the American Camp Association's claims that the reporting requirement infringes on camps' constitutional right to be free of illegal searches and seizures "couldn't be further from the truth."

"Frankly, under the liberal disclosure requirement of the federal courts, the American Camp Association's poorly conceived lawsuit is more likely to result in the public disclosure of private information sought from the camps than any of the activities of" the county health department.

[Byline: Andrew Denney]

